      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Subway Series, Dream and Nightmare</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Paul L Whiteley Sr letter comments on possible subway series in New York City this baseball season (Oct 14 Op-Ed by Roger Kahn)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Baseball Town, Again,'' by Roger Kahn (Op-Ed, Oct. 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Baseball Town, Again,'' by Roger Kahn (Op-Ed, Oct. 14):</p>
        <p>The years from 1947 to 1956 were the glory days of major league baseball. I was between the ages of 10 and 19 during that time span and a big fan.</p>
        <p>Radio, black and white TV, Mel Allen and Gillette's ''Look sharp, feel sharp, be sharp'' were familiar World Series fare. The warm, early-October sunshine of those afternoon games contrasts sharply with today's too-chilly night games.</p>
        <p>Greed played a major role in how the game has evolved. Still, baseball is an exciting game, New York City is a wonderful town, and Roger Kahn is a great writer. Nevertheless, a possible Subway Series in 2000 will never capture the magic of the Subway Series between 1947 and 1956.</p>
        <p>PAUL L. WHITELEY SR.  Louisville, Ky., Oct. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
